High Fiber “chocolate” Cake

Ingredients
1 cup of carob powder
Dark chocolate pieces (optional)
1 can of unsalted garbanzo beans drain (if salted, rinse and drain liquid)
4 eggs
3/4 cup of maple syrup
1/2 teaspoon of baking powder
1 tsp of vanilla
1 cup of sliced strawberries
 
Directions
 
Preheat your oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour a 9-inch round cake pan. Add the beans and eggs to a food processor and process until the beans and eggs are smooth. Add in your maple syrup, vanilla and baking powder to the food processor as well and mix in with the beans and egg mixture. Add the carob and give the processor another mix. Scrape down the sides of the food processor to make sure all the carob is mixed in. Pour the batter into your round cake pan and bake for approximately 40 minutes or until a toothpick inserted in the center of the cake returns clean. Once the cake is ready, allow to cool for about 15- 20 minutes. Top with strawberries! Bake for approximately 40 minutes or until a toothpick inserted in the center of the cake returns clean. Once the cake is ready, allow to cool for about 15- 20 minutes. Top with strawberries!

Some try to shame us moms 🙄BUT the reality is that NOT everyone has time to make Insta-perfect meals. There’s no one-size fits all approach. Y’all mamas know we have to do what works best for us and our families.

It’s totally okay if you opt for frozen foods over fresh for a quick and easy dinner. There’s no need to feel guilty or embarrassed about it, because you’re doing the best you can in a really tough situation, especially in this economy okay!!!

The truth is, frozen foods can be a really smart way to quickly get healthy and balanced meals on the table. Frozen foods are often packed with ingredients that are nutrient-rich and carefully chosen to provide the necessary vitamins and minerals your family needs. Plus, they’re typically free of preservatives and artificial colors and flavors. 

So if you’re a busy mom who needs to get dinner, or any meal, on the table fast and don’t have time to cook from scratch, don’t feel bad about reaching for the frozen food aisle. You can doll up a frozen pizza even and it is nutritious. 

We are doing the best we can! 

AGAIN, Frozen foods are more convenient, less stressful, and just as nutritious as cooking from scratch. So go ahead and grab those frozen foods with confidence, knowing that you’re taking care of your family in the best way you know how!

#easymeals #dietitian #mama #nutritiousfood #blacknutritionistmama

What foods are you eating to reduce inflammation? ❤️

🌱Inflammation is an incredibly common health issue, and it can be incredibly uncomfortable. Left unmanaged, inflammation can lead to serious health problems in the long run. So, it’s important to do what we can to reduce inflammation in our bodies.

🌱But how? Eating a variety of plant-based foods is one of the most effective ways to reduce inflammation. Although it may sound like you need to be a vegan to follow this advice, it’s simply not true. Plant-based eating is not the same as veganism; you don’t necessarily need to give up all animal products to reap the anti-inflammatory benefits of a plant-based diet.

🌱Removing inflammation is very person-specific and it’s important to find what works best for you. Each person’s approach will be different depending on their individual lifestyle needs and preferences. But by incorporating more plant-based foods into your diet along with plenty of exercise and relaxation activities you’ll be well on your way to reducing inflammation and improving your overall health.

#dietitian #inflammation #antiinflammatory #wellness #blacknutritionistmama

If you’re a new mom and your body is still adjusting to motherhood, don’t be too hard on yourself. It took nine months to put on the weight, so it stands to reason that it will take some time to get back to your pre-pregnancy shape.

Postpartum weight loss isn’t something you can achieve overnight. It takes time, hard work and dedication, but the results can be worth it.

The important thing to remember is that it’s not a race, and there are no quick fixes. Make sure you’re taking it slow and easy when you start your postpartum weight-loss journey. When you start feeling comfortable with a certain level of activity and intensity, gradually increase the difficulty and frequency.

Be careful not to get obsessed with numbers. They don’t give you the whole picture and doesn’t speak on composition. 

Also, make sure you’re drinking plenty of water and getting enough sleep, as much as you can with a baby 😂. Both are key components of good health, and hydration helps your body function efficiently when doing physical activities.

Keep in mind that as your body changes, your goals may need to change too. You’re unique and everyone’s postpartum weight-loss journey is different. Respect your body’s limits by listening to it and moderating your exercise selection and intensity; don’t try to push too far too soon.

Remember that patience is key – this is a long-term process and the results will be worth it if you stick with it. There’s no one-size-fits-all approach to losing postpartum weight, but trust the process and stay motivated!

#postpartum #postpartumjourney #dietitian nutritionist #wellness #weightlossjourney #blacknutritionistmama

How often are you eating plant based foods? 

🌱I believe in making life easy! So at least 85%, sometimes more, of the time my foods are plant based. But as y’all have seen, I will pull out a frozen 🍕 if I need too! 😂 

🌱It’s important for us to think about how we fuel our bodies and the effects different types of foods can have on our health. You might be surprised to learn that food has the potential to be a powerful source of medicine.

🌱What exactly do I mean by “food as medicine”? Well, it’s based on the idea that certain foods contain powerful components that can help with inflammation, control blood sugar, boost immunity and even potentially reduce your risk of some diseases. 

🌱The great thing is that incorporating more plant based 🍃foods into your lifetime doesn’t have to be complicated or overly time consuming. It’s can sometimes be as simple as making small but meaningful changes to the food you already eat.

🌱For instance, adding more fruits and vegetables to your meals can provide beneficial vitamins, minerals and antioxidants. Eating a variety of grains can provide extra fiber, vitamins and minerals. Choosing healthy fats like nuts, avocados and olive oil can provide essential fatty acids that the body needs for optimal functioning. 

🌱Now, this doesn’t mean you have to live on salads and smoothies if you don’t want to – you’re still able to enjoy your favorite foods while taking steps to make them healthier. And being plant based does not mean you are vegan either. 

🌱If you want to take a more holistic approach to nutrition, start by identifying any potential inflammation, imbalances or deficiencies and make gradual changes to increase your intake of nutrient-dense foods.

#inflammation #dietitian #foodismedicine #wellness #plantbased #blackdietitian #blacknutritionistmama

🤰🏾If you didn’t know, the last few years has increased maternal death rates. 

🤰🏾African American women face significantly higher rates of pregnancy-related deaths and life-threatening complications than white women. 

🤰🏾It's also important to note that Black women are more likely to have limited access to prenatal care and other critical health services due to a variety of factors, including poverty and lack of access to healthcare in underserved areas. Moreover, Black women are more likely to endure racism and other forms of discrimination when seeking health care, which can contribute to poorer health outcomes. 

🤰🏾My Black maternal experience was mainly a great one but knowing the statistics, I was fearful each and every time I was giving birth. Because no matter my background or access, the risks remained because I am a Black mother. 

🤰🏾Yes I knew my physicians and was quite comfortable with how they worked but there were so many factors that I had no control over and the nerves were always there. 

🤰🏾One thing that calmed my nerves the most is knowing that I had advocates that burned shit down if they needed to, respectfully. 

🤰🏾By investing in access to quality healthcare, improving access to health insurance programs, and ensuring greater accountability and oversight of maternal care services, we can help eliminate the disparities that exist between Black and white maternal health. 

🤰🏾In order for us to truly make progress, it's essential that we prioritize Black maternal health and commit to closing the gap in maternal health outcomes among all women, regardless of race. We must also ensure that every mother is afforded the same access to quality prenatal care, regardless of her race, socioeconomic status, or location. 

#blackmaternalhealthweek #maternalhealthmatters #blackmaternalhealth #blackmaternalmortality #maternalmortality #wellness #blacknutritionistmama

🍁But did you know that as a dietitian nutritionist who specializes in gut health, I still sometimes struggle with bloating too? 

🍁Foods that our body have a hard time digesting causes a build up in gas in our tummy’s that result in bloating. 

🍁These foods, for me, include gluten, lactose (dairy products), and even wheat (fructans). 

🍁I know people be quick to eliminate the above thinking they are the culprit, but the reality is what’s causing your bloating is specific to you and it will differ from person to person. 

🍁Find out what those foods are and start from there. You and your families gut microbiome is specific, treat it as such. ❤️❤️

Are you doing any of these??! ❤️❤️❤️


1.	COOK SMART 👩🏾‍🍳 🍱 🌮🌯🥙🥘
Make meals that everyone can eat so that you are not skipping meals because you were so focused on your family and children and forgot about yourself.  The kids including babies and toddlers can eat the same things you are eating; you may just need to mash some items with a fork or thin it out instead of making a whole new meal. 

2.	SMOOTHIES 🧉🍓🍑🥑🍍🥥🍉🥭
Smoothies are a perfect way to keep you satiated, hydrated and consuming nutrients. Make sure to always have a fat in the fruits and veggies you are blending to help in the absorption of all the good nutrients in the smoothie and it will also help keep you full. Nuts and avocadoes are a good way to do that. 

3.	SPICES 🌶️🫚🫑🌱
Spices are a win win okay! Cause not only are we adding in flavor so that everyone is more likely to eat, cause again we don’t want bland food, but now we know that the more spices we are adding the happier the good bacteria in our gut will be and the more they will thrive.

Which of these are your favorites?❤️❤️❤️

What I’m using changes but these are some of my current faves!!! They not only provide flavor but are great for you and the fams gut health! ❤️

1.	Cayenne Pepper
•	Capsaicin, the compound that gives red peppers their spicy heat, also gives it its anti-inflammatory properties, ability to prevent or stop the growth of cancer cells, also provides benefits for relieving pain.

2.	Garlic Powder
•	Its sulphur-containing compounds, known as thiosulphinates, which are responsible for its strong smell and flavor, have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant capabilities. One of its main active components, allicin, allows it to deliver antiviral, antifungal, and antibacterial benefits.

3.	Cloves
•	It is anti-inflammatory, anti-viral, and anti-bacterial. Supporting your immune system and your gut health. 

4.	Ginger
•	 Has been proven to be a great help for digestion because of its ability to reduce gas as well as nausea and vomiting.

5.	Turmeric
•	Powerhouse when it comes to its anti-inflammatory properties. It is anti-cancer, antioxidant, antiviral and so much more. Contains curcumin are known to reduce inflammation and even help in the management of joint pain, arthritis, heartburn, kidney problems, IBS, and even Alzheimer’s.

6.	Black Pepper
•	Once known as “black gold”. Piperine, the main ingredient found in black pepper, helps your body absorb more curcumin from Turmeric. 2000% more!!!

7.	Cinnamon
•	Contains cinnamaldehyde which provides prebiotic properties (promoting good bacteria), can help in the management of flatulence and digestive imbalances. 

8.	Cardamom
•	Relieves stomach discomfort, has cancer fighting compounds

9.	Onion Powder
•	Aids in digestion, boosts immunity, reduces inflammation

10.	Paprika
•	Promotes healthy digestion and maintenance of a healthy gut while fighting free radicals

Vitamin C is one powerful nutrient! If one of the little germs my kids bring home is able to pass the fences I’ve built, vitamin C will help me 🥊 knock it down every time. 

Vitamin C is water soluble which means it dissolves in water. So taking it with any fluid is enough for it to be absorbed. 

Taking too much a at a time is not always great for absorption so it is best to breakdown your dosage throughout the day on a regular basis. 

For the purposes of stopping that tickle in your throat 😂 go ahead and hit it with the high dose all at once.
